docs.abstract: A shareholder lawsuit claims the directors of Google’s parent company approved a payout for Andy Rubin, who was accused of sexual harassment, in order to “keep the matter quiet.”
docs.snippet: A shareholder lawsuit claims the directors of Google’s parent company approved a payout for Andy Rubin, who was accused of sexual harassment, in order to “keep the matter quiet.”
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — A shareholder lawsuit says the board of directors of Google’s parent company, Alphabet, played an “active and direct role” in approving a $90 million exit package for Andy Rubin, a senior executive, even though an investigation into a sexual harassment claim against him was deemed credible.

headline.main: Board Sued Over Google’s Exit Package for Accused Executive
headline.print_headline: Alphabet Sued Over Exit Deal for Accused Executive

byline.original: By Daisuke Wakabayashi and Kate Conger

docs.abstract: Unicorns like Lyft are finally going public, after large gains have been captured by elite early investors.
docs.snippet: Unicorns like Lyft are finally going public, after large gains have been captured by elite early investors.
docs.lead_paragraph: The latest generation of Silicon Valley start-ups is now sprinting to the public markets, raising hopes among large and small investors eager to invest in these high-profile, fast-growing firms.

headline.main: In This Tech I.P.O. Wave, Big Investors Grab More of the Gains

byline.original: By Matt Phillips and Erin Griffith

docs.abstract: About 26,000 students are caught in the meltdown at Dream Center. The Education Department has scrambled to salvage their educations after it approved an unlikely turnaround plan.
docs.snippet: About 26,000 students are caught in the meltdown at Dream Center. The Education Department has scrambled to salvage their educations after it approved an unlikely turnaround plan.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the Education Department approved a proposal by Dream Center, a Christian nonprofit with no experience in higher education, to buy a troubled chain of for-profit colleges, skeptics warned that the charity was unlikely to pull off the turnaround it promised.

headline.main: A College Chain Crumbles, and Millions in Student Loan Cash Disappears
headline.print_headline: Thousands Tripped Up as a College Chain Sinks

byline.original: By Stacy Cowley and Erica L. Green

docs.abstract: Regulators have said the bank cannot grow until it fixes practices that led to a series of sales scandals. Employees report limited progress.
docs.snippet: Regulators have said the bank cannot grow until it fixes practices that led to a series of sales scandals. Employees report limited progress.
docs.lead_paragraph: Wells Fargo has spent years publicly apologizing for deceiving customers with fake bank accounts, unwarranted fees and unwanted products. Its top executives say that because they have eliminated the aggressive sales targets that spurred bad behavior, the bank’s culture has changed.

headline.main: Wells Fargo Says Its Culture Has Changed. Some Employees Disagree.
headline.print_headline: A Bank Says It’s Reformed. Workers Differ.

byline.original: By Emily Flitter and Stacy Cowley
